<div id="review_4191640995" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4191640995" />
    <a title="Paul" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/104062321-paul"><img alt="Paul" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1643168251p2/104062321.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4191640995?book_show_action=true">Aug 26, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paul" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paul" href="/user/show/104062321-paul">Paul</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4191640995" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2591079292811021322">Wendell Berry has a lot of interesting things to say. He says these things well, often passionately. His writing moves me to sympathize with him, even agree with him.<br/><br/>However, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/146191.The_Unsettling_of_America_Culture_and_Agriculture' title='The Unsettling of America Culture and Agriculture by Wendell Berry' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Unsettling of America: Culture and Agriculture</a> is nothing more than a long conspritorial rant full of unsubstantiated claims. Do I like small farms? Of course I do. Berry does as well. But he takes this a step further, arguing that large food-growing operations are undermining our health, both phyisical and psychologica</span>
  <span id="freeText2591079292811021322" style="display:none">Wendell Berry has a lot of interesting things to say. He says these things well, often passionately. His writing moves me to sympathize with him, even agree with him.<br /><br />However, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/146191.The_Unsettling_of_America_Culture_and_Agriculture" title="The Unsettling of America Culture and Agriculture by Wendell Berry" rel="nofollow noopener">The Unsettling of America: Culture and Agriculture</a> is nothing more than a long conspritorial rant full of unsubstantiated claims. Do I like small farms? Of course I do. Berry does as well. But he takes this a step further, arguing that large food-growing operations are undermining our health, both phyisical and psychological. He makes these claims (and many, many other claims) without providing supporting evidence.<br /><br />The lack of evidence and the conspritorial thinking Wendell Barry employs forced me to put this book down. I may sympathise with the man, but the way the book is written makes it simply not worth finishing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2591079292811021322" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


