  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4331658404" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4331658404" />
    <a title="Russell Fox" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4729679-russell-fox"><img alt="Russell Fox" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1294062726p2/4729679.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4331658404?book_show_action=true">Nov 10, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Russell Fox" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Russell Fox" href="/user/show/4729679-russell-fox">Russell Fox</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4729679-russell-fox?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4729679-russell-fox?shelf=small-towns">small-towns</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4729679-russell-fox?shelf=communitarianism">communitarianism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4729679-russell-fox?shelf=public-spaces">public-spaces</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4729679-russell-fox?shelf=localism">localism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4729679-russell-fox?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4729679-russell-fox?shelf=agrarianism">agrarianism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4729679-russell-fox?shelf=environmentalism">environmentalism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4331658404" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1676852379688539777">I read this book many years ago; this year, I re-read it as part of a new class I had developed, focused on &quot;urban and environmental ideologies.&quot; I thought the book would work well as one example of a comprehensive perspective on how human communities can and should (but historically have mostly failed to) flourish productively in rural places informed by, but not genuflective to, the natural ecosystems around them. In the end, I don&apos;t think it served that purpose--but any introduction of studen</span>
  <span id="freeText1676852379688539777" style="display:none">I read this book many years ago; this year, I re-read it as part of a new class I had developed, focused on "urban and environmental ideologies." I thought the book would work well as one example of a comprehensive perspective on how human communities can and should (but historically have mostly failed to) flourish productively in rural places informed by, but not genuflective to, the natural ecosystems around them. In the end, I don't think it served that purpose--but any introduction of students to Berry's wonderful, thorough jeremiad about how economies dependent upon specialization and division have warped agriculture, agricultural education, and agrarians communities generally is worth doing in my book. Many of the students struggled mightily with the way Berry's deeply conservative and localist perspective on human society was expressed in this nearly half-century old book, and no one can pretend that he wasn't then, and still is today, a massive crank when it comes to matters of individual lifestyle and identity choices. All I can say is that: such failings don't take away from his attack on modernity's addiction to technology, choice, and growth. His language throughout is filled with pastoral power, and never more so than when we expresses his vision of a farms and farmers settled into the ecosystems around them: "A healthy farm will have trees on it - woodlands, where forest trees are native, but also fruit and nut trees, trees for shade and for windbreaks. Trees will be there for their usefulness: for food, lumber, fence posts, firewood, shade, and shelter. But they will also be there for comfort and pleasure, for the wildlife that they will harbor, and for their beauty. The woodlands bespeak the willingness to let live that keeps wildness flourishing in the settled place. A part of the health of a farm is the farmer;s wish to remain there. His long-term good intention toward the place is signified by the presence of trees. A family is married to a farm more by their planting and protecting of trees than by their memories or their knowledge, for the trees stand for their fidelity of kindness to what they do not know. The most revealing sign of ill health of industrial agriculture--its greed, its short-term ambitions--is its inclination to see trees as obstructions and to strip the land bare of them" (pp. 181-182).</span>
  <a data-text-id="1676852379688539777" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

